<page_title>Mass dependence of speed distributions of molecules</page_title>
<text>Mass dependence of speed distributions of molecules
    
  

Explanation: The big atoms are 10 times heavier than the small ones. The interatomic forces between a pair of big atom and small atom are identical in the strength, according to Newton&apos;s third law (they are called action and reaction forces in physics). But the acceleration of the big atom resulted from the action force is 10 times smaller than the acceleration of the small atom resulted from the reaction force. As a result, the big atom will move more slowly, because the velocity of an atom derives from its acceleration.

The question is: why isn&apos;t the mean speed of the big atoms exactly one tenth of that of the small atoms?

 
Note: If you are wondering why atoms leave the box, it is because periodic boundary conditions are applied to the above model.
 



</text>
